	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Good EU sugar crop in prospect, while quota abolition proposal leaked</h1>

			
			<h4>
												20 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Press reports indicate that the EU sugar beet crop is expected to be the largest in 6 years. It is projected that ‘EU beet growers will harvest 17.26 million tonnes in the 2011–12 crop year starting Oct. 1, ... up from 15.2 million a year earlier.’. Exceptional yields in France were reported, while Germany is set to enjoy an ‘exceptional’ harvest. Farmers are expected to increase the area under sugar beet by 4% in the coming crop season, and good crops are forecast in Ukraine and Russia. As a consequence, Europe as a whole is expected to cut its net sugar imports sharply in the coming season.</p><p>These developments take place against a backdrop of complaints from food manufacturers over a shortage of sugar in the market. In May 2011, some German retailers were limiting the amount of sugar that customers could buy to 4 kg per purchase. In a statement on 13 August 2011, representatives from Nestle complained that ‘there is a major issue in the EU of [there] not being enough sugar available to meet demand.’ The statement noted that EU sugar reforms had been ‘based on the assumption that world sugar prices would remain lower than prices in the EU which has not been the case. Consequently, the EU sugar market is not functioning as foreseen.’ Some sugar-based food manufacturers expect ‘prices for sugar based foods in the EU to rise 20% by April because of higher costs of the sweetener’.</p><p>In March 2011, white sugar ‘was selling in Europe at about 517 euros ($745) a ton, ... more than the reference price of 404.40 euros’. This led the EC to take action by expanding duty free TRQ access (to 500,000 tonnes) and releasing out of quota sugar on to the EU market (500,000 tonnes), to boost supplies. EC agriculture spokesperson Roger Waite maintained that ‘what we’ve seen is a one-off year’, with the EC taking the view that no structural problem exists.</p><p>Global sugar production for the 2011–12 season is expected to exceed demand by 9 million tonnes (despite some production problems in Brazil), and world market sugar prices are expected to fall. Rabobank are suggesting a price of around 21 cents/lb in the next 12 months and ‘a significant rise in inventories over 2011-12’, leaving stocks equivalent to 40% of consumption, a level ‘only slightly below its 10-year average’.</p><p>Other analysts (Commerzbank and Kingsman) suggest prices of around 25c/lb, while some say prices could stay as high as 30 cents/lb. These higher price levels would be supported by strong Chinese demand for sugar. However, on 6 September Czarnikow suggested that the sugar surplus could be as low as 4 to 5 million tonnes.</p><p>According to analysts, since most of the expanded EU production will be out of quota, most of the EU’s extra sugar production ‘will go into exports ... some will go into storage’ and some will be converted to ethanol. As a consequence, ‘domestic sugar users for human consumption will not be able to benefit from this strong production’. In this context Reuters reported on leaked EC proposals for the abolition of EU sugar production quotas from October 2016. Such a measure ‘is projected to lead to a 1.9% increase in the EU sugar beet area in 2020, and an 8.2% fall in EU sugar beet prices’, as well as ‘a 6.9% rise in EU sugar exports and 4.7% cut in imports’. Deferring reform until 2016 would, it is argued, ‘allow for a reasonable period of adjustment for operators in the sector’.</p><p>On 20 September 2011, the ACP Committee on Sugar expressed concern at the leaked proposal to abolish EU sugar production quotas, on the grounds that it would increase price volatility.</p>
		
		
