<a href="http://brussels.cta.int/index.php?option=com_k2&amp;id=6002:acp-queries-european-bid-to-abolish-sugar-quotas&amp;view=item&amp;Itemid=54" target="_self">http://brussels.cta.int/index.php?option=com_k2&amp;id=6002:acp-queries-...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Sugar, even at a free on board (fob) world market price of 21cents/lb, would still provide better returns than the EU cost insurance and freight (cif) reference price for ACP raw sugar which will remain in place until 1 October 2012. This is likely to support EU sugar prices, despite the bumper EU sugar harvest. This anomaly arises in part from the maintenance of the quota system, which under current rules means that out-of-quota sugar cannot be used for food purposes within the EU, unless an exceptional dispensation is made (as occurred in 2011). This accounts for Nestle’s concerns over the artificial shortage of sugar for the food processing sector, and is likely to sustain the price paid for ACP raw sugar above the current reference price.</p><p>However, current market conditions are likely to increase pressure for the abolition of sugar production quotas as part of the 2013 round of reform (hence the timely leak to Reuters), since it will be argued that the current regime is not working properly. In addition, the current bumper crop within the EU could be indicative of EU sugar companies positioning themselves for a post-quota sugar regime, with further reforms likely to see a further shaking out of uncompetitive sugar producers within the EU.</p><p>Quota abolition, by removing the distinction between in-quota and out-of-quota sugar production will effectively circumvent WTO constraints on EU exports, allowing EU sugar companies to take advantage of expanding demand for sugar elsewhere in the world (either from production from within the EU or across their expanding global network of companies). This could exert a downward pressure on world market prices and ease price pressures in the EU, to the detriment of ACP raw sugar suppliers.</p>
		</div>
		
